---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const post = {
 title: 'Custom Embroidered Hoodies & Sweatshirts: A Buyer\'s Guide',
 description:
 'Embroidered hoodies are the workhorse for cool-morning trades, branded crew gear, and giveaway swag. Here\'s how to pick the right blank — Carhartt SUP01, Champion S700, Independent Trading IND4000 — and when embroidery beats screen printing on hoodies.',
 category: 'Products',
 readTime: '8 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/service-embroidery.jpg',
 slug: 'custom-embroidered-hoodies-sweatshirts',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'Should hoodies be embroidered or screen printed?', a: 'Embroidery for chest logos, screen printing for back prints. The premium textured look of embroidered thread on a heavy fleece reads as quality; screen-printed chest logos can crack at the fold over time. For a single full-back design, screen printing wins on impact and cost. Most crews run a small embroidered chest logo + a screen-printed back if both are wanted.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the best blank hoodie for embroidery?', a: 'Carhartt SUP01 Midweight Hooded Sweatshirt is the trade-friendly default — heavyweight 10.5 oz cotton-poly fleece, takes embroidery cleanly, survives crew use. Champion S700 Powerblend is the lighter, athletic-feel option. Independent Trading IND4000 Heavyweight is the premium streetwear-leaning choice. Gildan 18500 is the budget option for crew-wide programs.' },
 { q: 'How many stitches does a hoodie chest logo take?', a: 'A standard left-chest hoodie logo runs 6,000-9,000 stitches at 3-3.5 inches wide. Slightly higher stitch count than a polo logo because hoodie fleece is thicker and needs higher density to read crisply. Larger chest placements (4-5 inches wide) push 12,000+ stitches.' },
 { q: 'Can you embroider on a zip-up hoodie?', a: 'Yes — zip hoodies embroider as cleanly as pullovers. The embroidery sits on the chest panel above or beside the zipper. Avoid placements that cross the zipper line; the metal teeth and stitch path don\'t mix well. Both Carhartt and Independent Trading make zip hoodie versions of their popular pullover blanks.' },
 { q: 'Are embroidered hoodies worth the cost vs screen printed?', a: 'For chest-logo-only programs, embroidery is comparable in cost at moderate quantities (24-100 pieces) and reads as a higher-end gift. For high-volume programs (200+ pieces) where cost is the driver, screen printing wins on per-piece pricing. For one-off or small runs (<24), embroidery wins on relative cost because there\'s less setup.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the minimum order for custom embroidered hoodies?', a: 'Most shops set 12-24 pieces as the practical floor. Below that, the per-piece price climbs because digitizing and setup is amortized over fewer shirts. For very small orders (4-12), expect higher per-piece pricing or a small-order surcharge.' },
 { q: 'Can you embroider on quarter-zip pullovers?', a: 'Yes — quarter-zips embroider the same as hoodies. Common for sales and management roles where the look is more polished than a full hoodie. Port Authority F228 and Sport-Tek ST253 are the most-ordered quarter-zip blanks for embroidery.' },
]

const schema = {
 '@context': 'https://schema.org',
 '@graph': [
 { '@type': 'Article', headline: post.title, description: post.description, image: `https://bighornthreads.com${post.image}`, datePublished: post.isoDate, dateModified: post.isoDate, author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Bighorn Threads', url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/' }, publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Bighorn Threads', logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/images/logos/bighorn-logo-color.png' } }, mainEntityOfPage: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` },
 { '@type': 'BreadcrumbList', itemListElement: [{ '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/' }, { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Blog', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/blog/' }, { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: post.title, item: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` }] },
 { '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })) },
 ],
}
---

<BaseLayout title={post.title} description={post.description} canonical={`https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/`} ogImage={post.image} type="article" publishedDate={post.isoDate}>
 <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
 <article class="bg-concrete">
 <header class="border-b border-hairline bg-paper">
 <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 pt-20 pb-12 sm:px-6 sm:pt-24 lg:px-8">
 <nav class="mb-6 font-mono text-xs text-ash" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/" class="hover:text-gold-700">Home</a><span class="px-2">/</span><a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-gold-700">Blog</a></nav>
 <span class="mb-3 inline-block text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600">{post.category}</span>
 <h1 class="mb-6 font-heading text-3xl font-bold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">{post.title}</h1>
 <p class="mb-8 text-xl leading-relaxed text-ash">A working buyer's guide to embroidered hoodies for crew programs, branded swag, and pre-dawn 5 AM Vegas starts.</p>
 <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-4 gap-y-2 border-t border-hairline pt-6 font-mono text-sm text-ash"><span class="text-gold-600">Bighorn Threads Team</span><span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span><span>{post.readTime}</span><span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span><time datetime={post.isoDate}>{post.date}</time></div>
 </div>
 </header>
 <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 pt-10 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><img src={post.image} alt="Custom embroidered Carhartt hoodie with company logo on the chest" width="1200" height="675" loading="eager" class="w-full border border-hairline object-cover" /></div>
 <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

 <aside class="mb-10 border border-hairline bg-panel p-7">
 <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600">Quick Answer</p>
 <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal sm:text-xl">Custom embroidered hoodies are the right call for crew programs where you want a chest-logo-only program with a premium textured look. Carhartt SUP01 Midweight is the trade-friendly default; Champion S700 Powerblend for athletic feel; Independent Trading IND4000 for premium. For full-back designs, switch to screen printing — embroidery doesn't fit a back-print scale.</p>
 </aside>

 <h2 id="when-hoodies" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">When Custom Hoodies Make Sense</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">For trades and contractor crews, hoodies fill a specific role:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Cool desert mornings.</strong> Pre-dawn 5 AM starts in Vegas summer (mandated by Nevada heat-stress guidance) need a layer crews shed by 8 AM. A branded hoodie is that layer.</li>
 <li><strong>Winter desert work.</strong> 38° at 6 AM in Pahrump in January isn't unusual. A heavyweight cotton-poly hoodie covers the cold mornings without the cost of a full insulated jacket.</li>
 <li><strong>Crew swag programs.</strong> Holiday gifts, milestone rewards, anniversary gear — branded hoodies are perennially popular and crews actually wear them off the clock.</li>
 <li><strong>Trade show and event crews.</strong> Industry events, AGC dinners, ribbon cuttings — a sharp branded zip-up hoodie hits a different note than a polo.</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="blanks" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">The Hoodie Blanks That Matter</h2>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Carhartt SUP01 Midweight Hooded Sweatshirt — the workhorse</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Heavyweight 10.5 oz cotton-poly fleece. The default for trade and construction crews — durable enough to survive a working environment, takes embroidery cleanly, available in colors that match most brand palettes. Slightly more expensive than the budget options but the durability difference is real.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Independent Trading IND4000 Heavyweight Hooded Sweatshirt — premium</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">12 oz cotton-poly fleece, slightly heavier and more expensive than the Carhartt SUP01. Streetwear-leaning fit, very popular with younger crew members and brands that want a "premium giveaway" feel. Embroiders cleanly.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Champion S700 Powerblend Eco — athletic feel</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Lighter weight (9 oz) than the Carhartt or Independent options, with a more athletic cut and a distinct softer hand. The right pick for crews who don't want the heavy trade-style hoodie look. Slightly higher cost than Gildan but lower than Carhartt.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Gildan 18500 Heavy Blend — budget</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">The budget option for high-volume crew programs where per-piece cost dominates. 8 oz cotton-poly, embroiders fine, lasts well for the price. The default at 50+ piece runs where margins matter.</p>

 <h2 id="decoration" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Decoration: Embroidery vs Screen Printing on Hoodies</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">The decoration choice depends on what you're decorating where.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Chest logos: embroider</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Embroidered chest logos on hoodies look premium and last as long as the hoodie itself. Screen-printed chest logos crack at the fold lines (around the body) over time as the fleece flexes. For chest-only programs, embroidery is the right call almost universally.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Full-back designs: screen print</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Embroidery doesn't scale to a full-back design — the stitch count and machine time make it cost-prohibitive. Screen printing is the standard for back logos, full-back designs, and any wraparound graphic. Pair a screen-printed back with an embroidered chest logo for a complete program.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Sleeve hits: embroider</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Sleeve hits (forearm or upper arm) embroider cleanly. Common for trade-local affiliations, certifications, or secondary brand marks.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">For broader context on the embroidery vs screen printing decision, see <a href="/blog/screen-printing-vs-embroidery-construction/" class="text-gold-600 underline decoration-gold-600/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">screen printing vs embroidery</a>.</p>

 <h2 id="costs" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">What Custom Embroidered Hoodies Cost</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Per-piece cost is driven by the same five factors as <a href="/blog/how-much-to-embroider-a-shirt/" class="text-gold-600 underline decoration-gold-600/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">embroidered shirts</a>: stitch count, blank cost, digitizing fee, decoration complexity, and quantity. Hoodie blanks cost more than tee blanks but the embroidery is comparable, so the per-piece cost is mostly driven by the blank choice.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Bulk discounts kick in at 24+ pieces and again at 144+. For crews of 12-24, expect comparable per-piece pricing across blanks because volume discounts haven't kicked in.</p>

 <h2 id="programs" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Hoodies in a Crew Program</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">A typical crew package allocates 1 hoodie per employee per year — enough for the cool morning rotation, replaced when worn out. For trade-show and event crews, additional hoodies in special colorways or premium blanks signal the event.</p>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">For larger operations, hoodies are managed through a <a href="/company-stores/" class="text-gold-600 underline decoration-gold-600/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">company store</a> with employee allowances and direct shipping. Common pattern: a standard hoodie included in the new-hire kit, replacement available on the company store after the first year.</p>

 <div class="mt-12 border border-hairline bg-gold-500/5 p-7 sm:p-9">
 <h2 class="mb-3 font-heading text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">Custom embroidered hoodies in Las Vegas</h2>
 <p class="mb-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Bighorn Threads runs custom embroidered hoodies for Vegas contractors, trade businesses, and crew programs. Send your logo and quantity — we'll quote per piece with all costs broken out.</p>
 <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex min-h-[48px] items-center gap-2 bg-gold-500 px-7 py-3 text-base font-bold text-charcoal transition-all hover:bg-gold-600">Get a Quote →</a>
 </div>
 </div>
 </article>
</BaseLayout>
